<tree expanded="true" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Reference"><frontmatter> <anchor>24563</anchor> <addr>johnstone-1984</addr>  <route>johnstone-1984.xml</route> <date>January 1, 1984</date> <authors><author><link href="peterjohnstone.xml" type="local">Peter T. Johnstone</link></author> </authors> <title>Open locales and exponentiation</title> <meta name="doi">10.1090/conm/030</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related/> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Definition"><frontmatter> <anchor>24565</anchor> <addr>jms-001M</addr>  <route>jms-001M.xml</route> <date>February 14, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The positive elements of a pointed dcpo</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An element <tex>u</tex> of a <link href="jms-001S.xml" type="local" title="Pointed dcpo">pointed</link> dpco <tex>A</tex> is called <em>positive</em> when for any semidirected subset <tex>I \subseteq  A</tex>, if <tex>u \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup{I}</tex> then <tex>I</tex> is inhabited. We will write <tex>\mathsf{pos} \,{u}</tex> to mean that <tex>u</tex> is a positive element.</p><p>(This is adapted from <link href="johnstone-1984.xml" type="local" title="Open locales and exponentiation">Johnstone</link>’s definition of positive elements of frames to the case of dcpos by <link href="dejong-2023-thesis.xml" type="local" title="Domain theory in constructive and predicative univalent foundations">Tom de Jong</link>.)</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>